    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i see. i guess we need to be careful with the tolerances then. when we're doing the QC inspections, are there specific visual indicators or physical tests we should use to determine if the weave density is bordering on being \"too closed\" or non-breathable?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "For QC, you can look for a few things, like a very flat, almost glassy surface texture under magnification, which can signal excessive density. A good indicator of breathability issues is how the fabric reacts to a simple moisture test—if it retains water too quickly or feels clammy after a short period, that's a red flag.\n\nAlso, check the yarn tension during the weave; if the threads look overly stressed or if you see any puckering or unevenness in the surface, that means the density is fighting the yarn's natural flexibility. A truly good fabric, even when dense, should have a slight, pleasing drape, not a stiff, unyielding rigidity.",
      "source": "target",
